onal name from Mogworthy in Rackenford (Devon). The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Mogga</i> + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Hugford was born in 1345, in Shropshire, England, his father, Walter Hugford, was 25 and his mother, Alice Middleton, was 21. He had at least 1 daughter with Margery de Pabenham. He died on 28 November 1404, in Solihull, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1345–28 Nov 1404":"1345–28. november 1404","1345–1404":"1345–1404","1349–1408":"1349–1408","1387–1476":"1387–1476","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1324–Female":"1324–Surnud","1349":"1349","1404":"1404","28 Nov 1404":"28. november 1404","1324":"1324","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1476":"1476","